## HTTP security headers in ASP.NET Core

```csharp
app.UseHsts();
app.UseHttpsRedirection();

app.Use(async (context, next) =>
{
    context.Response.Headers["X-Content-Type-Options"] = "nosniff";
    context.Response.Headers["X-Frame-Options"] = "DENY";
    context.Response.Headers["Referrer-Policy"] = "strict-origin-when-cross-origin";
    await next();
});
```

---

## XSS prevention in .NET

- Use `HtmlEncoder.Default.Encode()` when rendering user-supplied content in HTML
- Do not use `Html.Raw()` in Razor unless the source is guaranteed safe
- Set `Content-Security-Policy` headers appropriate to the application context

---

## Insecure deserialisation

- Never use `BinaryFormatter`; it is a known remote code execution vector
- Use `System.Text.Json` with strict options:

```csharp
var options = new JsonSerializerOptions
{
    PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true,
    UnknownTypeHandling = JsonUnknownTypeHandling.JsonNode  // .NET 6+
};
```

- Do not deserialise untrusted JSON into dynamic types or `object`

